The paper proposes a learning-from-demonstration approach for grounding actions from expert data and an algorithm for using these actions to perform a task in new environments. The approach is based on sampling-based motion planning and symbolic representation of a task. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of machine learning techniques, which further supports the likelihood of it belonging to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses a magnetic structure assembly task, which involves visual perception and manipulation, indicating that it could also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the adaptation of the approach to new environments, which suggests that it could also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
